---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageMeta from '@/components/PageMeta.astro';
import Diagram from '@/components/Diagram.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="Strategic alignment"
>
<PageMeta category="Governance" updated="Updated 2026-05-14" damaKa={["Data Governance"]} />

      <h1>Strategic alignment</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        The five external frameworks and strategies PDTF publicly aligns to. Each one
        constrains the design space — and each one is a stakeholder relationship to
        maintain.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout--key">
        <div class="callout__label">Published positioning</div>
        <p>
          From propdata.org.uk's About page, PDTF lists five "Strategic Alignment" partners:
          HMLR Strategy 2022+, DSIT National Data Strategy, DVSTF, W3C Verifiable
          Credentials, and the Trust Over IP Foundation.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-text-muted); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
          <strong>Provenance:</strong> <code>propdata.org.uk</code> is a legacy developer site that carries OPDA
          copyright but was <strong>not authored or approved by OPDA</strong> (OPDA has no editing access). Its
          positioning is recorded here for reference; specific technical approaches it presents — notably
          <strong>Decentralised Identifiers (DIDs)</strong> — are exploratory, not yet OPDA / MHCLG / DPMSG-ratified.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="fiveAlignments">The five alignments</h2>

      <Diagram caption="PDTF's published Strategic Alignment partners.">
flowchart LR
  PDTF["`Property Data
Trust Framework`"]:::infra

  HMLR[HMLR Strategy 2022+]:::service
  DSIT[DSIT National Data Strategy]:::service
  DIATF["`DVSTF
Digital Verification
Services Trust Framework`"]:::service
  VC[W3C Verifiable Credentials]:::data
  ToIP[Trust Over IP Foundation]:::data

  PDTF --- HMLR
  PDTF --- DSIT
  PDTF --- DIATF
  PDTF --- VC
  PDTF --- ToIP
</Diagram>

      <h2 id="hmlr">HMLR Strategy 2022+</h2>
      <p>
        HM Land Registry's published business strategy from 2022 onwards. Property
        modernisation, digitisation of registers, Local Land Charges Programme, the
        national LLC service that's been rolling out council-by-council since 2018.
      </p>
      <p>
        PDTF aligns by:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Schema overlays for HMLR-managed forms (OC1, LLC1, CON29DW)</li>
        <li>Architectural compatibility with HMLR's national LLC service</li>
        <li>Maria Harris on the DPMSG-equivalent forums HMLR convenes</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="nationalDataStrategy">DSIT National Data Strategy</h2>
      <p>
        The cross-government strategy for unlocking the power of data (originally
        DCMS-published, now DSIT-owned). PDTF positions itself as a sector-specific
        implementation of the strategy's principles — particularly around Smart Data
        and trusted data sharing across organisational boundaries.
      </p>

      <h2 id="dvstf">DVSTF — Digital Verification Services Trust Framework</h2>
      <p>
        UK government's published trust framework for digital verification services
        (the rename of the former DIATF). Run by DSIT. Property transactions involve
        heavy ID checks (estate agent, conveyancer, lender — each currently does their
        own). DVSTF's stated goal is to enable "verify once, use many times" identity
        proofing.
      </p>
      <p>
        PDTF aligns by:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Using W3C VCs / DIDs for participant identity — compatible model</li>
        <li>The PDTF DID Auth OAuth 2 Specification (in trust-framework/docs/) draws on DVSTF concepts</li>
        <li>Future: PDTF accreditation could recognise DVSTF-certified IDPs</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="vc">W3C Verifiable Credentials Data Model</h2>
      <p>
        The W3C standard for cryptographically verifiable claims about subjects. The
        SPDTF (Smart Property Data Trust Framework) is being structured around VCs — every property data point is a claim,
        with provenance, issued by an accredited participant, presented to relying
        parties.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our archive includes both VC Data Model 1.1 and 2.0 specs locally at
        <a class="resource-link" href="/library/resources#cat-external-references"><code>source/08-external-references/related-w3c-specs/</code></a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="toip">Trust Over IP Foundation</h2>
      <p>
        Linux Foundation project. The 4-layer governance + technical stack model that
        PDTF directly adopts. See the dedicated
        <a href="/governance/toip-governance">ToIP governance page</a>.
      </p>

      <h2 id="implicitAlignments">Implicit alignments — not on the published list but worth tracking</h2>

      <p>
        Five more relationships that effectively shape the design space, even though
        OPDA hasn't formalised them as "Strategic Alignment":
      </p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Framework / standard</th><th>Why it matters</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>UK Open Banking</strong> (OBL → JROC)</td>
            <td>The direct precedent. propdata.org.uk's own tagline: "Open Banking for Property Data". Raidiam — Sandbox partner — operates the UK Open Banking Directory. Borrow patterns wholesale.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>EU Data Spaces / IDS-RAM</strong></td>
            <td>European federated data ecosystem governance. Worth tracking for cross-border interoperability optionality, especially with Northern Ireland / Irish property transactions.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Schema.org</strong></td>
            <td>Used by Rightmove, Zoopla and most UK property listing sites. PDTF semantic model should align where they overlap (Property, Place, ResidentialAddress).</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>FAIR data principles</strong></td>
            <td>Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, Reusable. PDTF's "open" positioning maps directly onto FAIR.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>W3C Data on the Web Best Practices (DWBP)</strong></td>
            <td>35 best practices for publishing data on the web. Practical checklist for PDTF's published artefacts (schemas, examples, contexts).</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="kpis">Alignment KPIs we could propose</h2>

      <p>
        To make these alignments operational rather than nominal, each should have
        measurable criteria. Suggested first cut:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>HMLR</strong> — every HMLR-published form has a PDTF overlay; LLC1 / OC1 conformance test suite passes.</li>
        <li><strong>National Data Strategy</strong> — public data assets in PDTF have <code>dcat:</code> metadata for discoverability.</li>
        <li><strong>DVSTF</strong> — PDTF accreditation cross-recognises at least one DVSTF-certified IDP.</li>
        <li><strong>W3C VC</strong> — SPDTF conforms to VCDM 2.0 test suite.</li>
        <li><strong>ToIP</strong> — published governance documents for all 4 layers + cross-cutting docs (per <a href="/governance/toip-governance">ToIP page</a>).</li>
      </ul>
</Layout>
